message.content: One of the most significant events that happened in Guinea in the past 100 years was its independence from colonial rule. Guinea gained independence from France on October 2, 1958, becoming the first French colony in Sub-Saharan Africa to achieve independence. This event marked a significant milestone in the decolonization process and inspired other African nations to seek independence from their colonial rulers. The country's first President, Ahmed Sékou Touré, played a crucial role in leading Guinea towards its independence, establishing a socialist-oriented government, and promoting African unity. The independence of Guinea had a profound impact not only on the nation but also on the broader African continent, setting an example for others seeking liberation from colonial powers.
